# Destructuring in JavaScript

Destructuring is a syntax feature in JavaScript that enables us to efficiently extract and assign values from arrays or objects into individual variables, providing a more convenient way to work with them.

## Array Destructuring

```javascript
let array1 = ["Amazon", "Google"];
let company1 = array1[0];
let company2 = array1[1];
console.log(company1); // Amazon
console.log(company2); // Google

// Using array destructuring
let [company1, company2] = array1;
console.log(company1); // Amazon
console.log(company2); // Google
```

## Object Destructuring (Mostly used in LWC)

```javascript
let person = {
  Fname: 'Vaibhav',
  age: 25,
  country: 'India'
};

// Instead of:
// var name = person.name;
// var age = person.age;

// Use object destructuring:
let {Fname, age, country} = person;
console.log(Fname); // 'Vaibhav'
console.log(age); // 25 
console.log(country); // India
```
